<div1 type="letter">

<pb facs="nei.j4a.1.22" />


<note type="curatorial">27 Davis Coll <hi rend="caps">N Y</hi> Pub Lib</note>   <fw type="curatorial">22</fw> 

<opener>
<hi rend="caps">R. H. D.</hi>

<dateline>June 30th, 1908.</dateline>


<salute>My dear Neihardt: &#8212;</salute>
</opener>
<p>This is to wish you God-speed in your three thousand mile trip, &#8212; no matter what direction you take.</p>

<p>On the Fourth, I start for Canada, Temagami reserve, to be gone three weeks. If you address a letter to me at the Temagami Inn, Temagami Station, Ontario, Canada, I will get it. You are the only human being in the United States (or Canada) who knows my address.</p>

<p>I am glad you liked the decorations of the <title>Man-Song.</title> I hope, when we meet again, that we will have heard more of it sung in this country.</p>

<p>Notwithstanding the fact that you will be far away from your Mother at the moment you read this letter, I send her my compliments.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Yours always,</salute>




<address>
<addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Esq.</addrLine>

<addrLine>Fort Benton,</addrLine>

<addrLine>Montana.</addrLine>
</address>


<note>M. B.</note>
</closer>

</div1>
